<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>SINGLE REDUCTION CARRIERS: ROCKWELL - REASSEMBLE - INSTALL ONE-PIECE SPIGOT BEARING ASSEMBLIES</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="5">
        <title>INSTALL ONE-PIECE SPIGOT BEARING ASSEMBLIES</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Some spigot bearings are fastened to the drive pinion with a snap ring, some are fastened with
                        a peening tool, and some are a two-piece bearing assembly with the inner race pressed on the
                        nose of the pinion and the outer race pressed into its bore in the carrier.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <seqlist>
                <item>
                    <para>Put the drive pinion in a press, gear head (teeth) toward the top (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1400656">Figure 56</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Press the spigot bearing on the end of drive pinion until the bearing is flat against the gear
                        head. Use a sleeve of the correct size against the bearing inner race (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1400656">Figure 56</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Install the snap ring
                        <ftnref xrefid="fn1400601"/>* into groove in end of drive pinion with snap ring pliers (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1400657">Figure 57</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </item>
            </seqlist>
            <figure id="f1400656" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400656" filename="../figg14/G1400656.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 56. Put Drive Pinion in Press</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. PRESS</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SLEEVE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SPIGOT BEARING</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f1400657" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400657" filename="../figg14/G1400657.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 57. Install Snap Ring in Groove</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. SPIGOT BEARING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SNAP RING</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Some spigot bearings are held in position by peening the end of the drive pinion. Use the
                        following procedure (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1400658">Figure 58</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f1400658" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400658" filename="../figg14/G1400658.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 58. Peen Spigot Bearing on Drive Pinion</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Peen the Spigot Bearing on Drive Pinion</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Apply 6,614 lb. (3,000 kg) pressure on a .375 inch or 10 mm ball.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Peen the end of drive pinion at a minimum of five points (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400658">Figure 58</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">When a peen tool (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400659">Figure 59</hotlnk>) and press are used (refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s14006t_58.xml" xrefid="hl1400605">SPECIAL TOOLS</hotlnk>), calculate the pressure
                    required on the tool as follows.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400659" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400659" filename="../figg14/G1400659.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 59. Peen Tool</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. PUNCH</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. TUBE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">6,614 lb. (3,000 kg) x amount of balls in tool = pounds or kilograms</para>
                <para>Example: 6,614 lb. x 3 balls = 19,842 pounds</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Put the drive pinion and the tube of the peen tool in a press, spigot bearing toward the
                    top (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400660">Figure 60</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400660" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400660" filename="../figg14/G1400660.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 60. Put Drive Pinion and Tube of Peen Tool in Press</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. PRESS</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. SPIGOT BEARING</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Calculate the amount of pressure that will be required on the peen tool. See
                    specification and example calculation.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Put the punch of the peen tool over the end of the pinion and spigot bearing. Apply the
                    required amount of pressure on the punch (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400660">Figure 60</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>Do not align new points with grooves in end of drive pinion or in old points. If the new
                            peen points are put in the wrong areas, the spigot bearing will not be held correctly on the
                            pinion.
                        </para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rotate the punch as many times as required for a minimum of five points. Repeat Step 7
                    for each point.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>If a three ball peen tool is used, rotate the tool 180&#176; (degrees).</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
